console.log(sortedArr); // Output: ["abc", "def", "ghi", "hello", "world"]
```
Note that the `localeCompare()` method is case-sensitive, so uppercase letters will come before lowercase letters in the sorted array. If you want to ignore case, you can use the `toLowerCase()` or `toUpperCase()` method to convert both strings to the same case before comparing them:
```
function sortStrings(arr) {
  return arr.sort((a, b) => a.toLowerCase().localeCompare(b.toLowerCase()));
}
```
This will sort the array in a case-insensitive manner.

