for (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i) {
    arr[i] = i;
}
delete[] arr; // Don't forget to delete!
```

### 5. Use `std::make_unique` and `std::make_shared`

These functions create smart pointers with the correct type, reducing errors.

```cpp
// Example using std::make_unique
auto ptr = std::make_unique<int>(5);
```

### 6. Profile Your Application

Use profiling tools to identify memory-intensive areas of your code and optimize them accordingly.

### 7. Use Valgrind or AddressSanitizer

These tools help detect memory-related issues like leaks, dangling pointers, and use-after-free errors.

```bash
