A `NullPointerException` occurs when you try to use a null reference as if it were an object. This error is thrown by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) at runtime. Here are some common causes of `NullPointerException`:

1. Accessing an object's method or field without first checking if it is not null:
```java
MyObject obj = null;
obj.doSomething(); // NullPointerException
```
To fix this, you should check if the object reference is not null before calling its methods or accessing its fields:
```java
if (obj != null) {
    obj.doSomething();
} else {
    // Handle the case when obj is null
}
```
2. Calling a method on a null reference that creates new objects:
```java
MyObject obj = null;
obj.createNewObject().doSomething(); // NullPointerException
```
To fix this, you should check if the object reference is not null before calling methods that create new objects:
```java
if (obj != null) {
    MyObject newObj = obj.createNewObject();
    newObj.doSomething();
} else {
    // Handle the case when obj is null
}
```
3. Using a variable that has not been initialized or assigned to an object:
```java
MyObject obj;
obj.doSomething(); // NullPointerException
```
To fix this, you should initialize the variable with a new object reference:
```java
MyObject obj = new MyObject();
obj.doSomething();
```
4. Using a method that returns null when it fails to create an object:
```java
MyObject obj = getNewObject(); // Returns null if creation failed
if (obj != null) {
    obj.doSomething();
} else {
    // Handle the case when obj is null
}
```
To fix this, you should check if the method returns a non-null object reference before using it:
```java
MyObject obj = getNewObject();
if (obj != null) {
    obj.doSomething();
} else {
    // Handle the case when obj is null
}
```
By following these guidelines, you can avoid `NullPointerException` in your Java application and ensure that your code handles null references gracefully.

