A NullPointerException is thrown when you try to call a method on a null object. This could be due to several reasons:

1. The object has not been initialized: If an object hasn't been assigned any value, then trying to access its methods or properties will result in a NullPointerException.

2. The object is null: If the object itself is null (not assigned any value), then calling any method on it will also throw a NullPointerException.

3. The method does not exist: If you're trying to call an undefined or non-existent method on the object, you'll get a NullPointerException.

4. The object is null and the method does not exist: In this case, your program will throw a NullPointerException.

To fix this issue, you can do one of the following:

1. Check if the object is null before calling its methods. If it's null, return or throw an exception.

```java
public void someMethod(Object obj) {
    if (obj == null) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("The object cannot be null");
    }
    // rest of the code here
}
```

2. Initialize your object before using it.

3. If you're sure that the object will never be null, you can safely call methods on it without checking if it's null.

4. If you are certain that the method does exist and is not null, you could cast the null object to its correct type and then call the method.

```java
Object obj = null;
obj = (MyClass) obj; // This will throw a NullPointerException if obj is null
```
Remember that this approach can lead to ClassCastException if the cast is not successful, so it's generally better to check for null before calling methods.

